The stolen kiss

Celebration or just oppression?

May 12, 2021 • Rafael Maus • 2 min read

pinterest   sailor   nurse   kiss   chauvinism

This image was found on Pinterest

  • Source

For Years this pictured kiss was considered a love symbol. It was used for hundreds of advertisements, magazine covers and was mentioned in several Hollywood screenplays. The kiss, that was officially not staged, was also non consented. Despite iconic in the love lore, it only shows us one more page on the machismo history.
The picture was taken by Alfred Eisenstaedt on August 14th, 1945. That Tuesday is known as the V-J Day. The day that Imperial Japan officially surrendered to the Allied Forces, putting an end to World War II. George Mendonsa, “the Sailor”, was about to return to his duties in the US Navy when he received the news. Gathering with so many others, George went to Times Square to celebrate. And we were not alone. Rita Petry, his girlfriend, was with him. Greta Zimmer, “the Nurse”, still not believing in the news, was searching for a newspaper to confirm what was being said. As soon as they cross each other’s path, Greta was surprised by George overwhelmed by emotion due to the end of the war. George saw a Greta dressed as a Nurse, and said he was so grateful for those girls that have saved so many at the war, that to show his gratitude he kissed her like a Hollywood kiss. For those who saw the picture in 1945 that was so normal, so romantic. After all, it was a man kissing a woman. It was a sailor kissing a nurse. At the end of the war. Impossible to be more obvious in 1945, right? Well, for Greta it was not that obvious. Interviewed later, Greta has described the situation as very different from the man involved (the good kisser sailor man and the romantic photographer). Greta said that it was not romantic at all. She described George as an extremely strong man that surprised her by immobilizing her and then providing her a non-asked kiss. Although it was 1945, for Greta that was a shocking act. She also said that she saw the same thing happening with other women along the New York streets, including her again. A funny detail about this context: Greta was not even a Nurse. She was a Dental Assistant. Her uniform was only remarkably similar to the real Nurses at the US Army. 2021 and we still heard about violations and fetish with some professions. We must start to look at things the way they are, and not the way that conservatism and the patriarchy taught us to look. To help you think about that, how do you like this picture in colors? If it was pictured today? How would you see it? Commemoration or oppression?
